defaultI. defaultIs cycling safe?default&#xa0;
defaultIt
default is neither as dangerous as non
default-
defaultcyclists perceive it to 
defaultbe nor as safe as it should be 
defaulti
defaultn a civilised society such as ours.  It could be made much safer per mile cycled and the number of cyclists could be greatly increased for comparatively little compared with the amount spent on roads and the expenditure by the NHS on illness related to ob
defaultesity.
default&#xa0;
defaultCycling in traffic feels particularly 
defaultunsafe because however careful
default cyclist
defaults are
default, their safety is largely in the hands of drivers.  A cyclist who is dressed in bright clothing, wears a helmet. who has good lighting and who rides carefully and corr
defaultectly may still be wiped out 
defaultbe
default a motorist. If they are, they are largely unprotected and will be s
defaulteriously hurt o
defaultr killed.  Conversely, a careful driver who makes no mistake is unlikely to be involved in a serious accident and if they are, their car will 
defaultprovide a lot of protection for them. So cyclists are vulnerable and at the mercy of others to a much greater extent than motorists.
default&#xa0;
defaultII. What could be done to improve safety?default&#xa0;
defaultA. Segregation(see below)
default&#xa0;
defaultB.
default 
defaultTake steps to reduce the danger caused to 
defaultcyclists by vehicles
default&#xa0;default1. The
default Highway Code
default&#xa0;
defaultImprove the content and the emphasis of the highway 
defaultcode.
defaultThe
default Highway Code devotes only three paragraphs (211 – 213) to the care motorists should pay to cyclists,(
defaultincluding them with motorcyclists
default,
default which is potent
defaultially misleading
default and                    dangerous) and giving the impression that they are rather an afterthought rather than users with equal rights of access. The Code needs amendment to inculcate an understanding of cycling in the motorist, particularly
default of the difficulties and dangers involved in cycling, and how cycling differs from motoring. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Code should state that motorists should allow cyclists a minimum width of 1.5m when overtaking.
default&#xa0;
default2. Speed limits
default&#xa0;
defaultA 20mph limit should be the norm in urban a
defaultreas where segregated cycle facilities are lacking
default&#xa0;
defaultSpeed limits should be enforced preferably by traffic calming measures which are cycle
default-
defaultfriendly or by speed cameras.
default&#xa0;
default3. Driving test
default&#xa0;
defaultThe test should require the driver to demonstrate knowledge of defens
defaultive driving techniques to minimise the chance of hitting a cyclist.
default&#xa0;
defaultKnowledge about the position a 
defaultcyclist
default should take on the road should be part of the test.  Drivers should be aware that cyclists should not be hugging the kerb.
default&#xa0;
default4. Definition of 
defaultdangerous driving
default&#xa0;
defaultDefine "dangerous driving" realistically so that a driver who causes the death or serious injury of another by the way they have driven will in all cases be charged with dangerous driving.
default&#xa0;
default5. Penalty for killing a cyclist (or pedestrian
default)
default&#xa0;
defaultMake drivers more careful in the vicinity of cyclists (and pedestrians!) by making the loss of the driving licence mandatory in all cases where a driver is found responsible for the death of a cyclist or pedestrian. Prison is not an appropriate punishme
defaultnt; a period of being forbidden to drive is a more effective encouragement to people to drive carefully, particularly in the case of HGV drivers who are responsible for a disproportionate number of cyclist deaths.
default&#xa0;
default6. HGV's
default&#xa0;
defaultFit all HGV's with devices to 
defaultwarn the driver of the presence of a cyclist
defaultBan HGV's from city and town centres during the day unless segregated facilities for cyclists have been provided
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.Legalise cycling on footways beside fast roads
default&#xa0;
defaultLegalize cycling on footpaths beside fast road
defaults.  Ideally, it should be legalised where the speed limit is more than 30mph with power for Councils to apply for exemptions where necessary i.e. to ban cyclists from footpaths where pedestrian use would make cycling inappropriate.  A start could perhaps b
defaulte made by legalisation where the limit is above 40mph.  Clearly, cyclists must ride 
defaultsafely 
defaultwith
default 
defaultdue 
default consideration for other path users. 
default&#xa0;
default8. Cycle lanes: priority, width, usually free of parked vehicles
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultVehicles should cede priority to cycle lanes acros
defaults junctions and roundabouts.  This would play a part in making motorists more aware of cyclists.
default The change would, however, need wide publicity.
default  The lanes should be clearly marked.
default&#xa0;
defaultAll on
default-
defaultroad cycle lanes 
defaultshould
default have a minimum width of 1.5m
default.  Narrow lane
defaults are likely to increase danger to cyclists by causing them to ride in the gutter and encourage cars to squeeze past where there is insufficient room.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn all but exceptional circumstances, no parking should be allowed in cycle lanes.
default&#xa0;
default9. Signs to remind d
defaultrivers of minimum overtaking width
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs in 
defaultFrance
default, the space which should be allowed cyclists by overtaking vehicles should be emphasised by reminders on road signs.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
